 <!-- PAGE 6: MANAGING EXPECTATIONS -->
    <section class="instruction-page">
        <h1>What to Expect from AI Translation</h1>

        <div class="instructions-grid">
            <div class="left-column">
                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Realistic Expectations</h2>

                    <p><strong>Nubart TRANSLATE provides professional-grade simultaneous interpretation comparable to experienced human interpreters.</strong></p>

                    <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <strong>However, AI translation is NOT:</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Mathematical certainty (language is subjective)</li>
                            <li>Perfect under all conditions (neither are humans)</li>
                            <li>Infinitely customizable through glossaries</li>
                            <li>The same as copying text into DeepL or ChatGPT</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Why Simultaneous AI Translation ≠ Document Translation</h2>

                    <p><strong>Many clients expect results like DeepL or ChatGPT document translation. This comparison stems from a fundamental misunderstanding.</strong></p>

                    <h3>Document Translation (DeepL, ChatGPT):</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Works with <strong>complete texts</strong></li>
                        <li>System knows the end of each sentence before translating</li>
                        <li>Can optimize results with full context</li>
                        <li>No time pressure</li>
                        <li>Perfect text input (no audio issues)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>Simultaneous Interpretation (Nubart TRANSLATE):</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Happens <strong>live, in real-time</strong></li>
                        <li>Doesn't know how sentence will continue</li>
                        <li>Makes linguistic decisions based on anticipation and probability</li>
                        <li>Must transcribe speech first (accents, noise, imperfect mics)</li>
                        <li>Immediate delivery required</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <strong>The Double Challenge:</strong> Before translating, the AI must first understand the speaker. Converting human speech into reliable text in real-time—with accents, background noise, and imperfect microphones—is an enormous technical challenge, sometimes as complex as the translation itself.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>The analogy:</strong> Comparing simultaneous interpretation with document translation is like comparing a live broadcast with a studio-edited video. Both can be excellent, but they play by completely different rules.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Where AI Excels vs. Human Interpreters</h2>

                    <h3>AI Advantages:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>✅ Superhuman memory for technical terminology</li>
                        <li>✅ Excellent with lists of figures</li>
                        <li>✅ Never fatigued</li>
                        <li>✅ Instantly available</li>
                        <li>✅ Unlimited scalability</li>
                        <li>✅ Fraction of cost (humans: ~€500/day)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>AI Challenges (vs. skilled humans):</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Sometimes struggles to distinguish speaker voice from background</li>
                        <li>Can be "too precise" (replicates speaker errors)</li>
                        <li>May struggle with punctuation placement</li>
                        <li>Doesn't smooth or summarize redundant speech</li>
                        <li>Struggles with language mixing (code-switching)</li>
                        <li>Synthetic voice mispronounces foreign names/brands</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Language Mixing (Code-Switching) Limitation</h2>

                    <p><strong>Common scenario:</strong> Speaker presents in German but uses English expressions ("customer journey," "machine learning," "best practices").</p>

                    <p><strong>What happens:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Option 1:</strong> AI thinks English words are German and invents similar-sounding German words</li>
                        <li><strong>Option 2:</strong> AI switches to translating everything into a different language (e.g., Spanish) instead of keeping English terms in English</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <strong>Why this happens:</strong> The system is set to one source language (German). When it detects English words, it doesn't know whether to:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Keep them as English (loan words/technical terms)</li>
                            <li>Translate them to the target language</li>
                            <li>Treat them as mispronounced German</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Human interpreters handle this better</strong> because they understand context and know which terms to leave untranslated.</p>

                    <p><strong>What you can do:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Include English terms in glossary</strong> if you know speakers will use them (helps but doesn't guarantee success)</li>
                        <li><strong>Brief speakers</strong> to use the selected language consistently, or</li>
                        <li><strong>Use "Change language" button</strong> if switching between languages for entire sections</li>
                        <li><strong>Accept this limitation</strong> as a known trade-off of AI interpretation</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>This affects human interpreters too:</strong> A German interpreter expecting only German may stumble when the speaker suddenly uses English phrases. The difference is humans adapt faster.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Synthetic Voice Pronunciation Limitation</h2>

                    <p><strong>Common scenario:</strong> German speaker mentions "Fraunhofer" (German company). The transcription is correct, the translation correctly keeps the name unchanged, but the synthetic voice pronounces it with a strange accent instead of the German way.</p>

                    <p><strong>What happens:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Transcription:</strong> ✅ Correct ("Fraunhofer")</li>
                        <li><strong>Translation:</strong> ✅ Correct (name kept as "Fraunhofer")</li>
                        <li><strong>Text-to-Speech:</strong> ❌ Mispronounced (weird accent or wrong emphasis)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <strong>Why this happens:</strong> The text-to-speech (TTS) system pronounces words according to the target language's phonetic rules. When it encounters a foreign name in the text, it doesn't automatically know to switch to the original language's pronunciation rules.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example breakdown:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Speaker (German): "Fraunhofer" [pronounced correctly in German]</li>
                        <li>Transcription: "Fraunhofer" ✅</li>
                        <li>Translation to English: "Fraunhofer" ✅ (name unchanged)</li>
                        <li>English TTS voice: "Frown-hoffer" ❌ (English phonetic interpretation)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>This also affects:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Company names (BMW, Siemens, Xiaomi)</li>
                        <li>Product names (Geschäftsführer-Portal, 工業 4.0)</li>
                        <li>People's names (François, José, Müller)</li>
                        <li>Place names (München, København, Łódź)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>What you can do:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Include pronunciation guide in glossary</strong> (helps minimally - TTS still uses target language phonetics)</li>
                        <li><strong>Inform listeners</strong> that text translation is accurate even if voice pronunciation sounds odd</li>
                        <li><strong>Recommend text-only mode</strong> for events with many foreign names</li>
                        <li><strong>Accept this limitation</strong> - training TTS for each event's specific names is not currently feasible</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>Important context:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Human interpreters pronounce these correctly</strong> because they recognize the name's origin</li>
                        <li><strong>Listeners can read the correct spelling</strong> in the text translation, even if audio is mispronounced</li>
                        <li><strong>This is a known TTS limitation</strong> affecting all real-time translation systems</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Professional Excellence, Not Perfection</h2>

                    <p><strong>Both human and AI interpretation achieve professional excellence, not perfection.</strong></p>

                    <p>A human interpreter translating in writing, at home, with resources and time, might achieve near-perfect accuracy. That same interpreter working in real-time achieves 85-95% of that theoretical perfect translation.</p>

                    <p><strong>AI operates in the same professional range</strong> with different error patterns than humans.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="center-column">
                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Subject to External Conditions</h2>

                    <p><strong>Like human interpreters, AI translation quality depends on:</strong></p>

                    <table>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Factor</th>
                            <th>Impact</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Audio clarity</td>
                            <td>High impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Audio volume</td>
                            <td>High impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Speaker pace</td>
                            <td>Medium impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Speaker articulation</td>
                            <td>Medium impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Speaker accent</td>
                            <td>Low-medium impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Internet quality</td>
                            <td>Medium impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Environmental noise</td>
                            <td>High impact</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Room acoustics</td>
                            <td>High impact</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>

                    <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <strong>AI is not magic.</strong> It requires optimal input conditions just as human interpreters need good equipment, booth isolation, and clear delivery.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Managing Glossaries Realistically</h2>

                    <p><strong>Think of glossaries like briefing a human interpreter:</strong></p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>✅ A 15-page briefing document: Helpful</li>
                        <li>❌ A 200-page technical manual: Cognitive overload, counterproductive</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>Why Long Glossaries Backfire:</h3>
                    <p><strong>Neural translation works by probability models.</strong> Forcing one term changes probabilities for entire sentence. Force 50 terms = cascading errors.</p>

                    <h3>Best Practice:</h3>
                    <div class="alert alert-success">
                        <strong>15-20 high-impact terms only</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Company/product names</li>
                            <li>Sector-specific acronyms</li>
                            <li>Truly unique terminology</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Don't Include:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Common technical terms AI already knows</li>
                        <li>Terms with multiple contextual meanings</li>
                        <li>Stylistic preferences for correct translations</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="right-column">
                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>When AI Translation Works Best</h2>

                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Technical presentations</strong> with specialized vocabulary</li>
                        <li><strong>Business conferences</strong> with standard terminology</li>
                        <li><strong>Academic lectures</strong> in well-defined fields</li>
                        <li><strong>Product demonstrations</strong> with clear structure</li>
                        <li><strong>Panel discussions</strong> with prepared speakers</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Challenging Scenarios for AI</h2>

                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Highly colloquial language</strong> with idioms and slang</li>
                        <li><strong>Rapid-fire dialogue</strong> with speaker interruptions</li>
                        <li><strong>Poetry or wordplay</strong> relying on linguistic creativity</li>
                        <li><strong>Heavily accented speech</strong> (though AI handles most accents well)</li>
                        <li><strong>Poor audio conditions</strong> (echo, noise, low volume)</li>
                        <li><strong>Language mixing</strong> (e.g., German speaker using English expressions)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <strong>Note:</strong> Human interpreters also struggle with these scenarios. They're not AI-specific limitations.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Setting Event Attendee Expectations</h2>

                    <h3>Recommend communicating to attendees:</h3>

                    <p><strong>In pre-event materials:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>"AI-powered real-time translation will be available"</li>
                        <li>"Translation quality is comparable to professional human interpreters"</li>
                        <li>"All attendees should bring headphones for best experience"</li>
                        <li>"Translation available in 35+ languages"</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>Don't promise:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>❌ "100% accurate translation"</li>
                        <li>❌ "Perfect reproduction of speaker's voice"</li>
                        <li>❌ "Zero delay"</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="section-box">
                    <h2>Technology is Constantly Improving</h2>

                    <p>AI translation technology improves rapidly. What seems challenging today may work flawlessly next year.</p>

                    <p><strong>Current improvements underway:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Better accent recognition</li>
                        <li>Improved contextual understanding</li>
                        <li>More natural voice synthesis</li>
                        <li>Faster processing with lower latency</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="alert alert-success">
                        <strong>The Revolution:</strong> Technology has democratized professional interpretation. Events of any size can now offer multilingual access at a fraction of traditional cost.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>